WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Imagine you're an economics student and it's the start of the academic year.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:23.000
You're sitting in one of these chairs in the lecture venue and your lecturer is talking about changes in unemployment rates and productivity

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:26.000
and brings up this graph from your economics textbook,

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:30.000
showing the trends in change over time.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:34.000
Well, having just lived through 2020,

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:41.000
you likely know someone or know someone who knows someone who lost their job due to the COVID pandemic

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.000
and your eyes immediately avert to this part of the graph.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:47.000
What's going on here?

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:52.000
What would this graph look like if we could include more recent data?

00:00:52.000 --> 00:01:02.000
Wouldn't it be great if your lecturer could draw on a relevant recent experience to make the teaching more engaging

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.000
and also have the textbook resources to support this?

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:14.000
The problem is this figure from an economics textbook was manually produced in proprietary software,

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:20.000
where each element was individually placed by a designer according to their style sheet.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
It is very time intensive and expensive.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:35.000
Updating and reproducing figures such as this is one of the key contributing factors to the really slow revision cycles of such a textbook.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:42.000
Our world is rapidly advancing and changing, and although we may have the data available,

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:49.000
our educational resources quickly become outdated and likely stay so for several years.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:54.000
This is not a problem that is only common to the educational publishing industry.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:00.000
How can we invigorate such a traditional process to overcome this?

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:03.000
My name is Megan Beckett.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:10.000
I'm a data scientist from Cape Town, South Africa, and I'd like to tell you about how we at Exegetic Analytics

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:21.000
partnered with a publishing company in order to prototype a pipeline to automatically produce figures for an economics textbook.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:30.000
There are thousands of these images, and each has been meticulously manually handmade by the designers according to their style sheet.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:38.000
The first question the publishing house came to me with was, can you automate this so that we can easily update them?

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:43.000
Well, with R and the tidyverse, of course we can.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:49.000
The first step in the process was therefore to figure out an automated pipeline.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:59.000
We started out with the data in Excel files and various other sources, which were ingested into Google Sheets as a central repository.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:08.000
The reason for using Google Sheets instead of a database was that we still wanted it to be easily accessible to non-technical users,

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:13.000
so they could also access the data and update it as needed.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:26.000
Each figure is then governed by a central R script where the data is read in, the figure produced in ggplot, and then the main output focus was SVG.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:38.000
However, with such an automated workflow, we can also output multiple formats, useful in their various publishing platforms, whether it's EPUB, print, or the web.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:45.000
Furthermore, by taking advantage of the Plotly library and adding a single line of code to our scripts,

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:54.000
we can also create interactive versions of each figure for the web, further enhancing the teaching and learning experience.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:03.000
This entire process is wrapped up within an R package with several helper functions to help automate this pipeline.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:10.000
When we get to integrating with the publishing house's processes, this will likely become an API.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:19.000
So, we ticked the box of figuring out how to automate this pipeline so that the graphs can be easily updated.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:26.000
But the next question they came with was, well, can you make them look as good as our originals?

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:32.000
As publishers, it was very important to them that the figures looked good for teaching,

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:39.000
that they complied to their style guidelines, and that they were virtually indistinguishable from the originals.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:48.000
This second part of the project therefore focused on the aesthetics, and this is where ggplot really came to the party.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:53.000
And it's also a part of the project that I thoroughly enjoyed.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:05:02.000
On the left-hand side here, you can see an example piece from the style sheet that the designers worked with in order to produce the figures.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:05.000
This needed to be translated into code.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:12.000
The vast majority of the aesthetics of the figures was controlled with a custom ggplot theme.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:18.000
Here I've shown a simplified version on the right-hand side to demonstrate what I'm talking about.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:25.000
We started out with the base classic theme and then built upon that,

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:33.000
where each specification in the visual style sheet was translated into code as a specification to the theme.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:41.000
For example, the font families, the point sizes, colors and lines, and even the spacing around all of the elements.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:48.000
It really is quite incredible how much you can control the output of your ggplot figures.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:53.000
I'd like to show you some of the outputs of what we achieved.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:59.000
On the left-hand side, you can see the original, meticulously manual plot.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:08.000
The purpose here is not to read and understand these graphs, but rather to make a comparison between this and the aesthetically automated.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:15.000
This here is our example from the beginning, from the economics lecture, with an additional plot below.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:20.000
If you do spot any differences, please do tweet me, as I do really love doing this.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:28.000
Here is a second example, and what I want to point out here are some deliberate differences.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
You might have noticed this in the previous graph as well,

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:38.000
but there are some dotted lines, blue lines, that show the trends for different time periods.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:43.000
When I calculated these trends from the data and plotted them on the graph,

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:50.000
I noticed a stark difference, particularly for the 18th century, as indicated here.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:57.000
What I realized then is that the designer had visually looked at the data and placed the trend line by hand,

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:00.000
according to what they thought was best.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
This is very error-prone.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:08.000
So, not only is our plot on the right aesthetically automated,

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:14.000
but it is also more accurate than the original, as it is derived directly from the data.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:20.000
This third example was really quite a fun challenge to solve,

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:26.000
specifically around the layout and how we placed these dotted grey lines,

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:31.000
extending from points on the top graph to corresponding points on the bottom graph.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:39.000
As I mentioned, about 80% of the aesthetics of the plots was achieved with the ggplot theme.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:47.000
However, here I also used the grid-extra and ggtext and ggtable packages,

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:52.000
which really power the layout engine of ggplot.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:59.000
I was able to get into the underlying grobs and grid in order to produce such a layout.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:02.000
I really was quite proud of this image.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:09.000
This last example here shows some trend lines for different cities.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:16.000
What I want you to take note of, though, are the icons used in the legend, called keyglyphs.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.000
These are not standard keyglyphs that come with ggplot.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:29.000
Typically, each geom has an associated function that will draw the keyglyphs in the legend, if it's required.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:36.000
For example, geom.point has a keyglyph function called draw-key-point

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:41.000
that will then add points to the legend as icons, if needed.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:47.000
What we did was look at the ggplot code for how these keyglyph functions work

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:54.000
and create some of our own custom functions to manually draw these icons.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:09:03.000
For example, this one is a key path with a key symbol placed on the right-hand side of that path to obtain this icon.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:13.000
These keyglyph functions are then passed to the geom layer within the ggplot code

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:22.000
so that we can update these key legends accordingly to how the original looks.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:28.000
Having done this, the publishing house were now quite impressed with our skills

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.000
and starting to believe in us that we could actually do this.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:37.000
The next question then was, OK, so can you do this in all languages?

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.000
This economics textbook has been translated into several languages

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:48.000
and so we needed to figure out how to handle the automatic translation of these figures in our pipeline.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.000
This third step therefore focused on translation

00:09:53.000 --> 00:10:00.000
and the solution that we came up with was to capture the translated strings in a YAML file

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
which is then read into the R script for the figure.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:10.000
YAML, if you're not familiar with it, used to stand for Yes Another Markup Language

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:15.000
and it's now become the recursive acronym YAML Ain't Markup Language

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:20.000
to specifically distinguish its use as being data-oriented

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.000
rather than a traditional markup for documents.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:28.000
It's often used in configuration files

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:33.000
and you might have seen it or noticed it at the top of our markdown documents.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:34.000
That's YAML.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:39.000
It's very structured and importantly, it's human-readable.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:44.000
This is important for us because we needed the translators who are non-technical

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:49.000
to be able to easily work with the format in order to capture the translated strings.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:54.000
But at the same time, I have a structure that has a clear format to it

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:57.000
and it's data-oriented to work with in R.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:03.000
On the left-hand side here, you can see an example from one of our YAML files.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:08.000
Each of the languages is denoted by an abbreviated two-letter word

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:11.000
for example, EN for English.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:17.000
Each of the labels that then requires translation is assigned a variable name

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:20.000
that's common across all of the languages.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:22.000
For example, x-axis label.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:28.000
The value for this label is then the text that is the translated string.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:32.000
For example, year, ano, or warsi.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:38.000
In R, we then have the YAML package to work with these files.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:43.000
So the strings are read into R using the function read underscore YAML

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:48.000
as a list of lists, which I then convert into a data frame.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:54.000
Within the ggplot code, each of the labels that requires translation

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:58.000
is then substituted with that variable name.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:02.000
The list of languages that needs to be generated

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:06.000
is obtained from the first level in the hierarchy of the YAML file.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:09.000
And then I iterate over those languages

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:13.000
and replace the variable names with each translated string

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:16.000
as we generate the output for that translation.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:22.000
The fourth benefit of this process was that it allowed us

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:27.000
to give the translators some more custom control over the labels.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:31.000
What I mean by this is, for example, in some cases

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:35.000
we needed some part of the string to be in italics.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:37.000
For example, the unit.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:40.000
With just English, this is fairly straightforward to do

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.000
within the R script.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:46.000
However, if we take multiple languages into account,

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:50.000
how do we know which part of the string needs to be in italics?

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:54.000
This is where I use the ggtext package.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:58.000
This is a line from the theme function which I showed earlier

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:02.000
where we replaced the element text function

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:04.000
with element markdown.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.000
What this enables is that the translators can use

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:12.000
simple markdown in their strings, which is then converted

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:15.000
to display the correct output in the final image.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:20.000
For example, they could enclose a unit in asterisks

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:24.000
and this is then converted into italics in the final output.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:29.000
This worked well for labels that were accessed titles.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:32.000
However, we also have many labels that require translation

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:36.000
that are placed on the plot with geom label or geom text.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.000
In order to cater for this, what I did was again use

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:45.000
the ggtext package and create a function that corresponds

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:48.000
with the original ggplot to override it.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
For example, geom text.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:54.000
Here we use instead geom underscore rich text,

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:59.000
which again enables translators to be able to put

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:01.000
simple markdown into their strings.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:04.000
That's then catered for in the final output.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.000
One of the really interesting challenges to solve

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:12.000
with the translation was the different numbering systems

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:15.000
for different languages and how do we automatically

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:17.000
cater for this in a single R script.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.000
What do I mean by this?

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:24.000
Well, here you can see three graphs in three different languages.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:27.000
What I want you to do is take note of the y-axis

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:29.000
and the format of each of the numbers.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:34.000
On the left we have English and you can see that

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
the thousand separator is a comma.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:40.000
We then have Spanish, which has a space separator,

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:46.000
but only once the number is more than four digits long.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.000
Then we have the Finnish and here you can see

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:54.000
that the thousand separator is a space.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:57.000
So how do we cater for this in the R script?

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:01.000
The solution I came up with was to create

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:04.000
a number formatting function per language

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:07.000
which uses the number format function

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:11.000
to specify what the big mark should be

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:15.000
for the thousand separator and the decimal mark,

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:17.000
whether it should be a comma or a point.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:23.000
The key thing here is that each function for each language

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:26.000
has the same name as the two-letter abbreviated version

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.000
in the YAML file.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:33.000
This here shows English compared to Finnish,

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:35.000
which is denoted by F-I.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:42.000
The Spanish was a slightly more involved example and function.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:46.000
And what I did here was to iterate over the list

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:50.000
of numbers supplied as the labels and first check

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:53.000
whether the number is more than four digits long.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:56.000
If so, then it gets a space and otherwise

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:59.000
there's no space for the thousand separator.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:06.000
Within the ggplot code, within the R script,

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:08.000
the production of each of the languages

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:12.000
is handled within the for loop and as mentioned previously,

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
this list of languages is obtained

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:17.000
from the first level heading in the YAML file,

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:20.000
for example, E-N, E-S, F-I.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:25.000
In the ggplot code, I then use the very handy

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:28.000
match.fun function from base R

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:32.000
that takes the language input as a string

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.000
and then uses the number formatting function

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
that corresponds with that

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:40.000
in order to format the numbers for the Y axis

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:43.000
according to what is needed for that language.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:47.000
This here shows the Y axis, but it can just as easily be done

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.000
for the X axis.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:52.000
Having figured this last piece in the puzzle out

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:56.000
for how to automatically translate images

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:00.000
within our pipeline, I then went back to the publishers

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:04.000
and heard a resounding, let's do this from them.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:07.000
So we are now at a stage in the process

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:11.000
where we are figuring out how to integrate

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:15.000
with their publishing pipeline in order to automatically

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:18.000
and beautifully create thousands of images

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:21.000
for their economics textbook.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:24.000
Peeking into our workshop

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:27.000
from the perspective of the publishing industry,

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:30.000
what we have done may seem incomprehensible,

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:33.000
but I hope what I have demonstrated here

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:36.000
is that with a few familiar tools

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:38.000
applied in unconventional ways,

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:42.000
you can completely transform a conventional process.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:47.000
There are so many industries and processes out there

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:50.000
that are still very manual and time-intensive

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:53.000
and battling to keep up with our ever-changing world.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:56.000
They don't know it yet,

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:59.000
but they could really benefit from your skills.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:03.000
And from my experience, they won't necessarily come knocking at your door.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:06.000
So sit up and take notes of opportunities

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:09.000
where you can really add value.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:12.000
For me, I'm thinking of those economics students

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:16.000
sitting in their lecture venue at the start of the academic year.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:19.000
Not only would they have lived through the previous year,

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:22.000
however bizarre and unusual it might have been,

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:24.000
and come out different for it,

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:27.000
but now their textbook can too.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:29.000
Thank you.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:31.000
I do look forward to your thoughts and questions,

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:33.000
and please do get in touch.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
Thank you.

